 to the Atlantic have focused on geographical crossings by subjects, Gentic highlights the everyday moments of reading and thought in which discourses of nation, postcolonialism, and globalization come into conflict. Critics have often evaluated in isolation how ideology, ethics, affect, and the body inform identity; however, Gentic skillfully combines these approaches to demonstrate how the chronicle exposes everyday representations of self and community.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aGroup identityxPolitical aspectszLatin AmericaxHistoryy20th century. 0aGroup identityxPolitical aspectszSpainxHistoryy20th century. 0aNationalismzLatin AmericaxHistoryy20th century. 0aNationalismzSpainxHistoryy20th century. 0aNewspaper readingxPolitical aspectsxHistoryy20th century. 0aNewspapersxSections, columns, etcxPolitical aspectsxHistoryy20th century. 0aSubjectivityxPolitical aspectsxHistoryy20th century. 0aTimexPolitical aspectsxHistoryy20th century. 4aArea Studies : Hispanic Studies. 4aCommunication : Communication. 4aHistory : History. 4aLatin American, Caribbean, and Latinx Studies : Latin American Studies. 4aLiterature : Literary History. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Spanish & Portuguese.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438448602423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438448602/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles